# Welcome to the experiment for Infinite Impulse Response Filter Design
Here we see an example to demonstrate the use of the IIR filter design functions of MATLAB

## If you are looking only for the **CODE**:   [CLICK HERE](https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B0moyKGbvtKDV1A3andYVUp0SU0/view?usp=sharing)

## You can even find the **CODE** on [GITHUB HERE](https://github.com/kaustubhcs/Infinite-Impulse-Response-Filters/blob/master/IIR.m)

## If you are looking only for **FINAL RESULT**:   [CLICK HERE](https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B0moyKGbvtKDc21Bd3JGWFZfajg/view?usp=sharing)

# Working of *CODE*

### Infinite Impulse Response Filter Design. This code will prove to be classic example for proper use of the given functions for Butterworth filter, Chebyshev Type 1 filter and Chebyshev Type 2 Filter Design



### Inputs Provided


### Passband Attenuation
    Ap = 3;



### Sampling Frequency
    Fs = 500;



### Stopband Attenuation
    As = 60;



### Passband Frequency
    Wp = 40;



### Dividing by Sampling Frequeny
    Wp = Wp / Fs;



### Stopband Frequency
    Ws = 150;



### Dividing by Sampling Frequeny
    Ws = Ws / Fs;


### Derivation of order by butterord

    [n,Wn] = buttord(Wp,Ws,Ap,As);

### Formula for Order n of Butterworth filter


 ![Formula for Order n of Butterworth filter](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10541929/1b681f20-7432-11e5-9722-2788cb41ba71.png)



#### OR another simplified version will be



![Simplified Version](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10541931/1b693770-7432-11e5-83a4-587625024efe.png)


### Applying the Butterworth filter function
    [b,a] = butter(n,Wn);

### Converting to frequency domain.
    [h,w] = freqz(b,a);


### Since the obtained input was in Normalized Form we get it back by multiplying with Sampling Frequency
    W = w*Fs/pi;



### To remove the negative values of h we take absolute
    h = abs(h);

### The PLOT for Butterworth Filter

    figure();
    plot(W,h);
    title('Butterworth Filter')

![Butterworth](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10542163/d42a02ac-7433-11e5-8bbf-166a9f2b0c0c.jpg)

### Butterworth Filter Characteristics


![Butterworth Filter Characteristics](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10542238/6bb71236-7434-11e5-9292-72064dc5e632.jpg)

### Derivation of order

    [n,Wp] = cheb1ord(Wp,Ws,Ap,As);

### Applying the Chebyshev Type I filter function

    [b,a] = cheby1(n,Ap,Wp);

### Converting to frequency domain.
    [h,w] = freqz(b,a);


### Again since the obtained input was in Normalized Form we get it back by multiplying with Sampling Frequency
    W = w*Fs/pi;

### Again to remove the negative values of h we take absolute
    h = abs(h);

### The PLOT for Chebyshev Type I Filter

    figure();
    plot(W,h);
    title('Chebyshev Type I Lowpass Filter')

![Chebyshev Type I Filter](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10542164/d4520a68-7433-11e5-9e47-bc8b648c4a60.jpg)

### Derivation of order


    [n,Wp] = cheb2ord(Wp,Ws,Ap,As);

### Applying the Chebyshev Type II filter function

    [b,a] = cheby2(n,Ap,Wp);

### Converting to frequency domain.
    [h,w] = freqz(b,a);


### Again since the obtained input was in Normalized Form we get it back by multiplying with Sampling Frequency
    W = w*Fs/pi;


### Again to remove the negative values of h we take absolute
    h = abs(h);

%% The PLOT for Chebyshev Type II Filter
    figure();
    plot(W,h);
    title('Chebyshev Type II Lowpass Filter')

![Chebyshev Type II Filter](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7969023/10542195/0be00160-7434-11e5-946d-6e8c695321f6.jpg)


